Wash and dry all produce. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @Shallot{1}(thinly sliced). Zest and halve @Lime{1}(zested and halved). Thinly slice @Jalapeño{1}(thinly sliced into rounds), removing ribs and seeds for less heat.

In a #small bowl{}, combine shallot, juice from whole lime, @Sugar{1/4%tsp}, a pinch of @salt{pinch}, and as much jalapeño as you like. Set aside to pickle, stirring occasionally, until ready to serve.

In a second small bowl, combine @Sour Cream{4%tbsp}, @salt{}, @Pepper{}, and lime zest to taste. Add water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Set aside.

Drain @Corn{13.4%oz}, then pat dry with #paper towels{}. Heat a drizzle of @Vegetable Oil{2%tsp} in a large pan over high heat (if using a #nonstick pan{}, heat without oil). Add corn and cook, stirring occasionally, until lightly charred in spots, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> TIP: If corn begins to pop, cover pan.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #medium bowl{}.

Heat a drizzle of @Olive Oil{1%tsp} in same pan over medium-high heat. Add @Ground Pork{10%oz} and a pinch of salt and pepper. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned, ~{4-6%minutes}. Stir in @Southwest Spice Blend{1%tbsp} and half the @Tex-Mex Paste{1%unit} (all the paste for 4 servings); cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute}. Stir in @Chicken Stock Concentrate{1%unit} and @water{1/4%cup}. Cook until liquid has mostly reduced and pork is cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes} more.

Reserving veggies, pour pickling liquid to taste into bowl with corn. Stir in a drizzle of olive oil and a big pinch of salt and pepper. Wrap @Flour Tortillas{6} in damp paper towels and microwave until warm and pliable, ~{30%seconds}.

Divide tortillas between plates; fill with pork and corn. Top with crema and as many pickled veggies as you like. Serve.

> Mexican street corn is our favorite way to feel summer vibes all year round. No matter the weather, one bite of this tasty taco will make everything feel a whole lot sunnier. In this twist on Mexican esquites, crisp kernels are charred on the stovetop to develop a smoky-sweet flavor, then piled into steamy tortillas along with spiced pork, chili-lime crema, and a heap of pickled shallot and jalapeño. Yep, taco night just got a whole lot better.